    <tool>git</tool>
  </tools>

  <outputs>
    <artifact type="code">src/server/api/Sprk.Bff.Api/Services/Ai/Export/DocxExportService.cs — extended with GenerateFromMarkdownAsync method for markdown-to-DOCX conversion</artifact>
    <artifact type="code">src/server/api/Sprk.Bff.Api/Api/Ai/ChatWordExportEndpoints.cs (or addition to existing) — POST /api/ai/chat/export/word endpoint handler</artifact>
    <artifact type="code">src/server/api/Sprk.Bff.Api/Models/Ai/Chat/WordExportRequest.cs — request model with content, filename, sessionId, metadata</artifact>
    <artifact type="code">src/server/api/Sprk.Bff.Api/Models/Ai/Chat/WordExportResponse.cs — response model with speFileId, wordOnlineUrl, sizeBytes, generatedAt</artifact>
  </outputs>

  <acceptance-criteria>
    <criterion testable="true">`POST /api/ai/chat/export/word` with valid markdown content returns `201 Created` with a `wordOnlineUrl` field</criterion>
    <criterion testable="true">The generated .docx file is accessible in the matter's SPE container file browser after the call</criterion>
    <criterion testable="true">The `wordOnlineUrl` opens the file in Word Online when navigated to in a browser</criterion>
    <criterion testable="true">Markdown headings (`# Title`) are rendered as DOCX Heading1 style in the generated file</criterion>
    <criterion testable="true">Calling with empty `content` returns `422 Unprocessable Entity` with ProblemDetails</criterion>
    <criterion testable="true">Calling without valid session authorization returns `401 Unauthorized`</criterion>
    <criterion testable="true">`dotnet build` passes with no errors</criterion>
  </acceptance-criteria>

  <notes>
    The tenant SharePoint hostname for Word Online URL construction is likely in the form
    `{tenantName}.sharepoint.com`. This may be derivable from the SPE container's tenant context
    in `ChatHostContext`, or it may be configured in appsettings as `SharePoint:TenantHostname`.
    Check `SpeFileStore.cs` for how SPE URLs are constructed for other operations to find the
    tenant hostname.

    The spec assumption about a "basic Spaarke document template" — if no template file exists,
    create a minimal one: document header with "SPAARKE - CONFIDENTIAL" text, document footer with
    page number, Calibri font, standard margins. Store the template as an embedded resource in the
    BFF project (`Resources/DocxTemplate.docx`) and use it as the base for all export operations.

    The markdown-to-OpenXML conversion does NOT need to be exhaustive — focus on the markdown
    patterns that AI models actually produce in analysis output: headings, bold, paragraphs, and
    simple bullet/numbered lists. Tables and code blocks can be treated as plain paragraphs if
    the OpenXML implementation is complex to set up in this iteration.
  </notes>

  <execution>
    <skill>.claude/skills/task-execute/SKILL.md</skill>
